International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 18 Dec 2008
Source: Eurosurveillance Vol. 13, Issue 51 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=19077>


"European cluster of imported falciparum malaria from Gambia."
T Jelinek1, C Schade Larsen2, H Siikamaki3, B Myrvang4, P Chiodini5,
J Gascon6, L Visser7, A Kapaun4,8, G Just-Nubling9

1. Berlin Centre for Travel and Tropical Medicine, Berlin, Germany
2. Department of Infectious Diseases, Aarhus University Hospital,
Skejby, Denmark
3. Helsinki University Central Hospital, Division of Infectious
Diseases, Department of Medicine, Helsinki, Finland
4. Department of Infectious Diseases, Ullevaal University Hospital,
Oslo, Norway
5. Hospital for Tropical Diseases and Health Protection Agency
Malaria Reference Laboratory, London School of Hygiene and Tropical
Medicine, United Kingdom
6. International Health Centre, Hospital Clinic, Barcelona Centre for
International Health Research (CRESIB), Barcelona, Spain
7. Department of Infectious Disease, Section Travel Medicine, Leiden
University Medical Centre, Leiden, the Netherlands
8. Section Clinical Tropical Medicine, Heidelberg University
Hospital, Heidelberg, Germany
9. Klinik II, Centre for infectious and tropical diseases , J.W.
Goethe University, Frankfurt/Main, Germany

Abstract
A cluster of 56 patients returning from Gambia with falciparum
malaria has been noted in several countries of the European Union
since September this year [2008]. TropNetEurop, the European Network
on Imported Infectious Disease Surveillance, collected and reported
the cases. Lack of awareness and, consequently, of prophylactic
measures against malaria were apparent in the majority of patients.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[2]
Date: 22 Dec 2008
From: David Conway <dconway@mrc.gm>

The vast majority of all tourists stay in the coastal resort area, so
it is fully expected that most of the European tourists who recently
were reported to have returned with malaria in the Eurosurveillance
articles would have stayed there. We know that malaria transmission
persists in this area, and there have been cases this year [2008]
among local people and expatriate residents. Of course, the important
thing to emphasize is that there is no part of The Gambia that is
malaria free, and the recommendation for chemoprophylaxis for
visitors should be reinforced.

The MRC, NMCP, and NGO partners (CIAM) are analyzing 2008 data from a
number of health centres, including those previously analysed and
reported for the period until the end of 2007 in the recent Lancet
article. Malaria in most health facilities appears to be continuing
to decline, particularly upcountry in places where the decline had
previously been less marked than at the coast.

Community based surveys have also recently shown lower prevalences
than ever seen previously; these are being written up with a
manuscript hopefully available in January 2009, which we would be
glad to get your comment on. We have noticed in at least one facility
in the coastal region that numbers of cases are higher in 2008 than
in the previous 2 years, so it seems that the distribution is now
more patchy spatially, and we need to be alert to the possibility of
very local resurgences.

If you and the other European investigators could get details on the
hotel names and dates of stay for each case, we could help
investigate whether there was a micro-focus of "high" transmission or
not. We would not need further details of itineraries, such as day
trips, as nearly all transmission of malaria here occurs at night.

--
Dr David J Conway
Head of Malaria Research Programme
Medical Research Council Laboratories
Fajara, P.O. Box 273
Banjul, The Gambia
<dconway@mrc.gm>

